declarations.description:
This mixin is a port of [IronScrollTargetBehavior](https://github.com/PolymerElements/iron-acroll-target-behavior)
that works with LitElements.

`ScrollTargetMixin` allows an element to respond to scroll
events from a designated scroll target.

Elements that consume this mixin can override the `_scrollHandler`
method to add logic on the scroll event.

Returns if a element is tabbable. To be tabbable, a element must be

Returns the normalized element tabindex. If not focusable, returns -1.
It checks for the attribute "tabindex" instead of the element property
`tabIndex` since browsers assign different values to it.
e.g. in Firefox `<div contenteditable>` has `tabIndex = -1`

members.name: _hasLowerTabOrder
members.description:
Returns if element `a` has lower tab order compared to element `b`

with tabindex > 0.
If both have same tabindex, it returns false.

declarations.name: pushScrollLock

parameters.name: element
parameters.description: The element that should lock scroll.

declarations.description:
Push an element onto the current scroll lock stack. The most recently
pushed element and its children will be considered scrollable. All
other elements will not be scrollable.

Scroll locking is implemented as a stack so that cases such as
dropdowns within dropdowns are handled well.

declarations.name: removeScrollLock

parameters.name: element
parameters.description: The element to remove from the scroll lock stack.

declarations.description:
Remove an element from the scroll lock stack. The element being
removed does not need to be the most recently pushed element. However,
the scroll lock constraints only change when the most recently pushed
element is removed.

A target input field to observe.

members.name: _suggestions
members.description: List of suggestion that are rendered.

members.name: _loading
members.description: True when user query changed and waiting for `source` property update

members.name: source
members.description:
List of suggestions to render.
If the array items are strings they will be used to render a suggestions and
to insert a value.
If the list is an object the each object must contain `value` and `display`
properties.
The `display` property will be used in the suggestions list and the
`value` property will be used to insert the value to the referenced text field.

members.name: loader
members.description:
Set this to true if you use async operation in response for query event.
This will render a loader when querying for more suggestions.
Do not use it it you do not handle suggestions asynchronously.

members.name: openOnFocus
members.description: If true it will opened suggestions on input field focus.

members.name: disabled
members.description: When set it ignores any events on the input field.

members.name: verticalAlign
members.description:
The orientation against which to align the element vertically
relative to the text input.
Possible values are "top", "bottom", "middle", "auto".

members.name: verticalOffset
members.description:
A pixel value that will be added to the position calculated for the
given `verticalAlign`, in the direction of alignment. You can think
of it as increasing or decreasing the distance to the side of the
screen given by `verticalAlign`.

If `verticalAlign` is "top" or "middle", this offset will increase or
decrease the distance to the top side of the screen: a negative offset
will move the dropdown upwards; a positive one, downwards.

Conversely if `verticalAlign` is "bottom", this offset will increase
or decrease the distance to the bottom side of the screen: a negative
offset will move the dropdown downwards; a positive one, upwards.

members.name: horizontalAlign
members.description:
The orientation against which to align the element horizontally
relative to the text input. Possible values are "left", "right",
"center", "auto".

members.name: horizontalOffset
members.description:
A pixel value that will be added to the position calculated for the
given `horizontalAlign`, in the direction of alignment. You can think
of it as increasing or decreasing the distance to the side of the
screen given by `horizontalAlign`.

If `horizontalAlign` is "left" or "center", this offset will increase or
decrease the distance to the left side of the screen: a negative offset
will move the dropdown to the left; a positive one, to the right.

Conversely if `horizontalAlign` is "right", this offset will increase
or decrease the distance to the right side of the screen: a negative
offset will move the dropdown to the right; a positive one, to the left.

members.name: scrollAction
members.description:
Determines which action to perform when scroll outside an opened overlay
happens. Possible values: lock - blocks scrolling from happening, refit -
computes the new position on the overlay cancel - causes the overlay to
close

attributes.description: When set it ignores any events on the input field.

attributes.name: verticalAlign
attributes.description:
The orientation against which to align the element vertically
relative to the text input.
Possible values are "top", "bottom", "middle", "auto".

attributes.name: verticalOffset
attributes.description:
A pixel value that will be added to the position calculated for the
given `verticalAlign`, in the direction of alignment. You can think
of it as increasing or decreasing the distance to the side of the
screen given by `verticalAlign`.

If `verticalAlign` is "top" or "middle", this offset will increase or
decrease the distance to the top side of the screen: a negative offset
will move the dropdown upwards; a positive one, downwards.

Conversely if `verticalAlign` is "bottom", this offset will increase
or decrease the distance to the bottom side of the screen: a negative
offset will move the dropdown downwards; a positive one, upwards.

attributes.name: horizontalAlign
attributes.description:
The orientation against which to align the element horizontally
relative to the text input. Possible values are "left", "right",
"center", "auto".

attributes.name: horizontalOffset
attributes.description:
A pixel value that will be added to the position calculated for the
given `horizontalAlign`, in the direction of alignment. You can think
of it as increasing or decreasing the distance to the side of the
screen given by `horizontalAlign`.

If `horizontalAlign` is "left" or "center", this offset will increase or
decrease the distance to the left side of the screen: a negative offset
will move the dropdown to the left; a positive one, to the right.

Conversely if `horizontalAlign` is "right", this offset will increase
or decrease the distance to the right side of the screen: a negative
offset will move the dropdown to the right; a positive one, to the left.

attributes.name: scrollAction
attributes.description:
Determines which action to perform when scroll outside an opened overlay
happens. Possible values: lock - blocks scrolling from happening, refit -
computes the new position on the overlay cancel - causes the overlay to
close

attributes.name: noAnimations
attributes.description: Removes animation from the dropdown.

attributes.name: noTargetControls
attributes.description: When set it won't setup `aria-controls` on target element.

attributes.name: noTargetValueUpdate
attributes.description:
When set the element won't update the `value` property on the
target when a selection is made.

attributes.name: fitPositionTarget
attributes.description: When set it fits the positioning target width.

attributes.name: positionTarget

attributes.name: ignoreDropdownStyling
attributes.description:
The component sets CSS variables on the dropdown element by default.
When this property is set then the component ignores setting these styles, 
but you have to apply styles to the `anypoint-dropdown` element.
The drop down element is not in the shadow DOM so the application has access to it.

declarations.description: `anypoint-chip` A compact material design element that represent and input, attribute, or action. A chip contains a label and optionally an icon and remove icon. Remove icon is predefined. However icon can be any HTML element with `slot="icon"` attribute. Per material design guidelines the icon is rounded. ## Example ```html Biking ``` The "Biking" is the label rendered next to the icon. The chip also renders built-in remove icon. Clicking on the icon dispatches `chipremoved` custom event only. It does not remove the chip from the document as the application logic might use different ways of removing elements from dom than web platform APIs.

members.name: source
members.description:
List of suggestions to render when the user type in the input field.

Each array item can be a string which will be compared to user input.
If the item is an object is must contain the `value` property which
is used to compare the values. It can also contain an `icon` property
which value is an instance of `SVGTemplateResult` from `lit-html`
library.

If the suggestion item contains `id` property it's value will be returned
as a value of the input. Otherwise `value` is used.

### Example

```json
[
 "item 1",
 {
   "value": "Other item",
   "icon": svg`...`
 },
 {
   "value": "Rendered label",
   "id": "returned-value"
 }
]
```

members.name: autocapitalize
members.description:
Binds this to the `<input>`'s `autocapitalize` property.

Possible values are:

- `off` or `none`: No autocapitalization is applied (all letters default to lowercase)
- `on` or `sentences`: The first letter of each sentence defaults to a capital letter;
 all other letters default to lowercase
- `words`: The first letter of each word defaults to a capital letter; all other letters default to lowercase
- `characters`: All letters should default to uppercase

attributes.name: source
attributes.description:
List of suggestions to render.
If the array items are strings they will be used for display a suggestions and
to insert a value.
If the list is an object the each object must contain `value` and `display`
properties.
The `display` property will be used in the suggestions list and the
`value` property will be used to insert the value to the referenced text field.

Handler for the resize event dispatched by the children.

members.description:
Tasks executed when opened changes: prepare for the opening, move the
focus, update the manager, render opened/closed.

members.description:
Tasks which cause the overlay to actually open; typically play an
animation.

members.name: _renderClosed
members.description:
Tasks which cause the overlay to actually close; typically play an
animation.

members.name: _onAnimationFinish
members.description:
Called when animation finishes on the dialog (when opening or
closing). Responsible for "completing" the process of opening or
closing the dialog by positioning it or setting its display to

members.name: noAutoFocus
members.description:
Set to true to disable auto-focusing the overlay or child nodes with
the `autofocus` attribute` when the overlay is opened.

members.name: noCancelOnEscKey
members.description: Set to true to disable canceling the overlay with the ESC key.

members.name: noCancelOnOutsideClick
members.description: Set to true to disable canceling the overlay by clicking outside it.

members.name: closingReason
members.description:
Contains the reason(s) this overlay was last closed (see `closed`). `OverlayElement` provides the `canceled`
reason; implementers of the behavior can provide other reasons in
addition to `canceled`.

members.name: restoreFocusOnClose
members.description: Set to true to enable restoring of focus when overlay is closed.

members.name: allowClickThrough
members.description:
Set to true to allow clicks to go through overlays.
When the user clicks outside this overlay, the click may
close the overlay below.

members.name: alwaysOnTop
members.description: Set to true to keep overlay always on top.

members.name: _manager
members.description: Shortcut to access to the overlay manager.

members.name: _focusedChild
members.description: The node being focused.

members.name: opened
members.description: True if the overlay is currently displayed.

members.name: canceled
members.description: True if the overlay was canceled when it was last closed.

members.name: _canceled
members.description: True if the overlay was canceled when it was last closed.

members.name: withBackdrop
members.description:
Set to true to display a backdrop behind the overlay. It traps the focus
within the light DOM of the overlay.

members.name: scrollAction
members.description:
Determines which action to perform when scroll outside an opened overlay
happens. Possible values: lock - blocks scrolling from happening, refit -
computes the new position on the overlay cancel - causes the overlay to
close

members.name: backdropElement
members.description: The backdrop element.

members.name: _focusNode
members.description: Returns the node to give focus to.

members.name: _focusableNodes
members.description:
Array of nodes that can receive focus (overlay included), ordered by
`tabindex`. This is used to retrieve which is the first and last focusable
nodes in order to wrap the focus for overlays `with-backdrop`.

If you know what is your content (specifically the first and last focusable
children), you can override this method to return only `[firstFocusable,
lastFocusable];`

Keeps track of the focused child. If withBackdrop, traps focus within
overlay.

members.name: _onCaptureEsc
members.description: Handles the ESC key event and cancels (closes) the overlay.

members.description:
Handles TAB key events to track focus changes.
Will wrap focus for overlays withBackdrop.

Will call notifyResize if overlay is opened.

members.description: Updates the references to the first and last focusable nodes.

parameters.name: callback
parameters.description: Always bound to `this`

members.description: Debounces the execution of a callback to the next animation frame.

members.name: __saveScrollPosition
members.description: Memoizes the scroll position of the outside scrolling element.

members.name: __restoreScrollPosition
members.description: Resets the scroll position of the outside scrolling element.

members.name: fitInto
members.description: The element to fit `this` into.

members.name: sizingTarget
members.description:
The element that will receive a `max-height`/`width`. By default it is
the same as `this`, but it can be set to a child element. This is useful,
for example, for implementing a scrolling region inside the element.

members.name: noOverlap
members.description:
Will position the element around the positionTarget without overlapping
it.

members.name: positionTarget
members.description:
The element that should be used to position the element. If not set, it
will default to the parent node.

members.name: horizontalAlign
members.description:
The orientation against which to align the element horizontally
relative to the `positionTarget`. Possible values are "left", "right",
"center", "auto".

members.name: verticalAlign
members.description:
The orientation against which to align the element vertically
relative to the `positionTarget`. Possible values are "top", "bottom",
"middle", "auto".

members.name: dynamicAlign
members.description:
If true, it will use `horizontalAlign` and `verticalAlign` values as
preferred alignment and if there's not enough space, it will pick the
values which minimize the cropping.

members.name: horizontalOffset
members.description:
A pixel value that will be added to the position calculated for the
given `horizontalAlign`, in the direction of alignment. You can think
of it as increasing or decreasing the distance to the side of the
screen given by `horizontalAlign`.

If `horizontalAlign` is "left" or "center", this offset will increase or
decrease the distance to the left side of the screen: a negative offset
will move the dropdown to the left; a positive one, to the right.

Conversely if `horizontalAlign` is "right", this offset will increase
or decrease the distance to the right side of the screen: a negative
offset will move the dropdown to the right; a positive one, to the left.

members.name: verticalOffset
members.description:
A pixel value that will be added to the position calculated for the
given `verticalAlign`, in the direction of alignment. You can think
of it as increasing or decreasing the distance to the side of the
screen given by `verticalAlign`.

If `verticalAlign` is "top" or "middle", this offset will increase or
decrease the distance to the top side of the screen: a negative offset
will move the dropdown upwards; a positive one, downwards.

Conversely if `verticalAlign` is "bottom", this offset will increase
or decrease the distance to the bottom side of the screen: a negative
offset will move the dropdown downwards; a positive one, upwards.

members.name: autoFitOnAttach
members.description: Set to true to auto-fit on attach.

members.name: fitPositionTarget
members.description: When set it fits the positioning target width.

members.name: _defaultPositionTarget
members.description:
The element that should be used to position the element,
if no position target is configured.

members.name: _localeHorizontalAlign
members.description: The horizontal align value, accounting for the RTL/LTR text direction.

members.name: __shouldPosition
members.description: True if the element should be positioned instead of centered.

members.name: fit
members.description: Positions and fits the element into the `fitInto` element.

members.name: _discoverInfo
members.description: Memoize information needed to position and size the target element.

members.name: resetFit
members.description:
Resets the target element's position and size constraints, and clear
the memoized data.

members.name: refit
members.description:
Equivalent to calling `resetFit()` and `fit()`. Useful to call this after
the element or the `fitInto` element has been resized, or if any of the
positioning properties (e.g. `horizontalAlign, verticalAlign`) is updated.
It preserves the scroll position of the sizingTarget.

members.name: position
members.description: Positions the element according to `horizontalAlign, verticalAlign`.

members.name: constrain
members.description:
Constrains the size of the element to `fitInto` by setting `max-height`
and/or `max-width`.

members.name: center
members.description:
Centers horizontally and vertically if not already positioned. This also
sets `position:fixed`.

members.name: notifyResize
members.description:
Can be called to manually notify a resizable and its descendant
resizables of a resize change.

members.name: assignParentResizable
members.description:
Used to assign the closest resizable ancestor to this resizable
if the ancestor detects a request for notifications.

members.name: stopResizeNotificationsFor
members.description:
Used to remove a resizable descendant from the list of descendants
that should be notified of a resize change.

members.name: resizerShouldNotify

parameters.name: element
parameters.description: A candidate descendant element that implements `ResizableElements`.

members.description:
This method can be overridden to filter nested elements that should or
should not be notified by the current element. Return true if an element
should be notified, or false if it should not be notified.

members.name: _subscribeIronResize

parameters.name: target
parameters.description: Element to listen to for `resize` events.

members.description:
Subscribe this element to listen to `resize` events on the given target.

Preferred over target.listen because the property "renamer" does not
understand to rename when the target is not specifically "this"

members.name: _unsubscribeIronResize

parameters.name: target
parameters.description: Element to listen to for `resize` events.

members.description:
Unsubscribe this element from listening to to `resize` events on the
given target.

Preferred over target.unlisten because the property "renamer" does not
understand to rename when the target is not specifically "this"

nodes in order to wrap the focus for overlays `with-backdrop`.

children), you can override this method to return only `[firstFocusable,
lastFocusable];`

members.name: sizingTarget
members.description:
The element that will receive a `max-height`/`width`. By default it is
the same as `this`, but it can be set to a child element. This is useful,
for example, for implementing a scrolling region inside the element.

members.name: noOverlap
members.description:
Will position the element around the positionTarget without overlapping
it.

members.name: positionTarget
members.description:
The element that should be used to position the element. If not set, it
will default to the parent node.

members.name: dynamicAlign
members.description:
If true, it will use `horizontalAlign` and `verticalAlign` values as
preferred alignment and if there's not enough space, it will pick the
values which minimize the cropping.

members.name: horizontalOffset
members.description:
A pixel value that will be added to the position calculated for the
given `horizontalAlign`, in the direction of alignment. You can think
of it as increasing or decreasing the distance to the side of the
screen given by `horizontalAlign`.

If `horizontalAlign` is "left" or "center", this offset will increase or
decrease the distance to the left side of the screen: a negative offset
will move the dropdown to the left; a positive one, to the right.

Conversely if `horizontalAlign` is "right", this offset will increase
or decrease the distance to the right side of the screen: a negative
offset will move the dropdown to the right; a positive one, to the left.

members.name: verticalOffset
members.description:
A pixel value that will be added to the position calculated for the
given `verticalAlign`, in the direction of alignment. You can think
of it as increasing or decreasing the distance to the side of the
screen given by `verticalAlign`.

If `verticalAlign` is "top" or "middle", this offset will increase or
decrease the distance to the top side of the screen: a negative offset
will move the dropdown upwards; a positive one, downwards.

Conversely if `verticalAlign` is "bottom", this offset will increase
or decrease the distance to the bottom side of the screen: a negative
offset will move the dropdown downwards; a positive one, upwards.

members.name: _localeHorizontalAlign
members.description: The horizontal align value, accounting for the RTL/LTR text direction.

members.name: __shouldPosition
members.description: True if the element should be positioned instead of centered.

members.name: fit
members.description: Positions and fits the element into the `fitInto` element.

members.name: _discoverInfo
members.description: Memoize information needed to position and size the target element.

members.name: resetFit
members.description:
Resets the target element's position and size constraints, and clear
the memoized data.

members.name: refit
members.description:
Equivalent to calling `resetFit()` and `fit()`. Useful to call this after
the element or the `fitInto` element has been resized, or if any of the
positioning properties (e.g. `horizontalAlign, verticalAlign`) is updated.
It preserves the scroll position of the sizingTarget.

members.name: position

members.name: constrain
members.description:
Constrains the size of the element to `fitInto` by setting `max-height`
and/or `max-width`.

members.name: center
members.description:
Centers horizontally and vertically if not already positioned. This also
sets `position:fixed`.

members.name: notifyResize
members.description:
Can be called to manually notify a resizable and its descendant
resizables of a resize change.

members.name: assignParentResizable
members.description:
Used to assign the closest resizable ancestor to this resizable
if the ancestor detects a request for notifications.

members.name: stopResizeNotificationsFor
members.description:
Used to remove a resizable descendant from the list of descendants
that should be notified of a resize change.

members.name: resizerShouldNotify

parameters.name: element
parameters.description: A candidate descendant element that implements `ResizableElements`.

members.description:
This method can be overridden to filter nested elements that should or
should not be notified by the current element. Return true if an element
should be notified, or false if it should not be notified.

members.name: _subscribeIronResize

parameters.name: target
parameters.description: Element to listen to for `resize` events.

members.description:
Subscribe this element to listen to `resize` events on the given target.

Preferred over target.listen because the property "renamer" does not
understand to rename when the target is not specifically "this"

members.name: _unsubscribeIronResize

parameters.name: target
parameters.description: Element to listen to for `resize` events.

members.description:
Unsubscribe this element from listening to to `resize` events on the
given target.

Preferred over target.unlisten because the property "renamer" does not
understand to rename when the target is not specifically "this"

declarations.description:
Accessible dropdown menu for Anypoint platform.

The element works perfectly with `anypoint-listbox` which together creates an
accessible list of options. The listbox can be replaced by any other element
that support similar functionality but make sure it has an appropriate aria
support.

See README.md file for detailed documentation.

declarations.description:
`anypoint-icon-item`
An Anypoint icon list item is a convenience element to make an item with icon. It is an
interactive list item with a fixed-width icon area.
This is useful if the icons are of varying widths, but you want the item
bodies to line up. Use this like a `<anypoint-item>`. The child node with the slot
name `item-icon` is placed in the icon area.

members.name: verticalAlign
members.description:
The orientation against which to align the element vertically
relative to the `positionTarget`. Possible values are "top", "bottom",
"middle", "auto".

members.name: horizontalAlign
members.description:
The orientation against which to align the element horizontally
relative to the `positionTarget`. Possible values are "left", "right",
"center", "auto".

members.name: verticalOffset
members.description:
A pixel value that will be added to the position calculated for the
given `verticalAlign`, in the direction of alignment. You can think
of it as increasing or decreasing the distance to the side of the
screen given by `verticalAlign`.

If `verticalAlign` is "top" or "middle", this offset will increase or
decrease the distance to the top side of the screen: a negative offset
will move the dropdown upwards; a positive one, downwards.

Conversely if `verticalAlign` is "bottom", this offset will increase
or decrease the distance to the bottom side of the screen: a negative
offset will move the dropdown downwards; a positive one, upwards.

members.name: horizontalOffset
members.description:
A pixel value that will be added to the position calculated for the
given `horizontalAlign`, in the direction of alignment. You can think
of it as increasing or decreasing the distance to the side of the
screen given by `horizontalAlign`.

If `horizontalAlign` is "left" or "center", this offset will increase or
decrease the distance to the left side of the screen: a negative offset
will move the dropdown to the left; a positive one, to the right.

Conversely if `horizontalAlign` is "right", this offset will increase
or decrease the distance to the right side of the screen: a negative
offset will move the dropdown to the right; a positive one, to the left.

members.name: dynamicAlign
members.description:
If true, it will use `horizontalAlign` and `verticalAlign` values as
preferred alignment and if there's not enough space, it will pick the
values which minimize the cropping.

members.name: openAnimationConfig
members.description:
An animation config. If provided, this will be used to animate the
opening of the dropdown. Pass an Array for multiple animations.
See `neon-animation` documentation for more animation configuration
details.

members.name: closeAnimationConfig
members.description:
An animation config. If provided, this will be used to animate the
closing of the dropdown. Pass an Array for multiple animations.
See `neon-animation` documentation for more animation configuration
details.

members.name: noAnimations
members.description:
Set to true to disable animations when opening and closing the
dropdown.

members.name: allowOutsideScroll
members.description:
By default, the dropdown will constrain scrolling on the page
to itself when opened.
Set to true in order to prevent scroll from being constrained
to the dropdown when it opens.
This property is a shortcut to set `scrollAction` to lock or refit.
Prefer directly setting the `scrollAction` property.

members.name: autocapitalize
members.description:
Binds this to the `<input>`'s `autocapitalize` property.

Possible values are:

- `off` or `none`: No autocapitalization is applied (all letters default to lowercase)
- `on` or `sentences`: The first letter of each sentence defaults to a capital letter;
 all other letters default to lowercase
- `words`: The first letter of each word defaults to a capital letter; all other letters default to lowercase
- `characters`: All letters should default to uppercase

members.name: _checkInputValidity
members.description:
Because of the `value` property binding to the input element the value on
input element changes programmatically which renders input element's validation
valid even if it isn't. This function runs the steps as the regular input
validation would, including input validation.

This is a convenience method to set `anypoint` property on this element

members.name: attrForItemTitle
members.description:
The attribute to use on menu items to look up the item title. Typing the
first letter of an item when the menu is open focuses that item. If
unset, `textContent` will be used.

members.name: useAriaSelected
members.description:
When set it adds `aria-selected` attribute to currently selected item.

The `aria-selected` attribute is invalid with default role of this
element ("menu"). If you manually change the role to some other that
accepts `aria-selected` attribute on children then set this property.

members.name: highlightAriaSelected
members.description:
When set the effect of calling `highlightNext()` or `highlightPrevious()`
will be setting `aria-selected` attribute. For proper accessibility use
with the combination with `useAriaSelected` attribute.

members.description: Currently focused in the menu item.

members.description: Handler that is called when the down key is pressed.

members.name: _onEscKey
members.description: Handler that is called when the esc key is pressed.

members.name: _resetTabindices
members.description:
Resets all tabindex attributes to the appropriate value based on the
current selection state. The appropriate value is `0` (focusable) for
the default selected item, and `-1` (not keyboard focusable) for all
other items. Also sets the correct initial values for aria-selected
attribute, true for default selected item and false for others.

members.name: select

parameters.name: value
parameters.description: the value to select.

members.description:
Selects the given value. If the `multi` property is true, then the selected
state of the `value` will be toggled; otherwise the `value` will be
selected.

members.name: focusPrevious
members.description:
Focuses the previous item (relative to the currently focused item) in the
menu, disabled items will be skipped.
Loop until length + 1 to handle case of single item in menu.

members.name: focusNext
members.description:
Focuses the next item (relative to the currently focused item) in the
menu, disabled items will be skipped.

members.name: highlightNext
members.description:
Highlights, by setting the `highlight` css class, the next available element.
If there's no highlighted item but there is a selection (focused item)
then a next item after the selection is selected.

members.name: highlightPrevious
members.description:
Highlights, by setting the `highlight` css class, the previous available element.
If there's no highlighted item but there is a selection (focused item)
then a previous item before the selection is selected.

parameters.name: isSelected
parameters.description:
True if the item should be shown in a
selected state, otherwise false.

members.description:
Mutates items in the menu based on provided selection details, so that
all items correctly reflect selection state.

changes.

members.name: emphasis
members.description:
Button emphasis in the UI.

Possible values:
- `low` - Text buttons are typically used for less important actions.
- `medium` - Outlined buttons are used for more emphasis than text buttons due to the stroke.
- `high` - Contained buttons have more emphasis, as they use use a color fill and shadow.

Default is "low".

declarations.description:
Material design: [Bottom sheets](https://material.google.com/components/bottom-sheets.html#)

# `<bottom-sheet>`

Bottom sheets slide up from the bottom of the screen to reveal more content.

### Example

```html
<bottom-sheet>
   <paper-icon-item>
     <anypoint-icon src="inbox.png" item-icon></anypoint-icon>
     Inbox
   </paper-icon-item>
   <paper-icon-item>
     <anypoint-icon src="keep.png" item-icon></anypoint-icon>
     Keep
   </paper-icon-item>
   <paper-icon-item>
     <anypoint-icon src="hangouts.png" item-icon></anypoint-icon>
     Hangouts
   </paper-icon-item>
 </bottom-sheet>
```

### Positioning

Use the `fit-bottom` class to position the bar at the bottom of the app and with full width;

Use `center-bottom` class to display the bar at the bottom centered on a page.

members.name: horizontalAlign
members.description:
The orientation against which to align the element horizontally
relative to the `positionTarget`. Possible values are "left", "right",
"center", "auto".

members.name: verticalAlign
members.description:
The orientation against which to align the element vertically
relative to the `positionTarget`. Possible values are "top", "bottom",
"middle", "auto".

members.name: dynamicAlign
members.description:
If true, it will use `horizontalAlign` and `verticalAlign` values as
preferred alignment and if there's not enough space, it will pick the
values which minimize the cropping.

members.name: horizontalOffset
members.description:
A pixel value that will be added to the position calculated for the
given `horizontalAlign`, in the direction of alignment. You can think
of it as increasing or decreasing the distance to the side of the
screen given by `horizontalAlign`.

If `horizontalAlign` is "left" or "center", this offset will increase or
decrease the distance to the left side of the screen: a negative offset
will move the dropdown to the left; a positive one, to the right.

Conversely if `horizontalAlign` is "right", this offset will increase
or decrease the distance to the right side of the screen: a negative
offset will move the dropdown to the right; a positive one, to the left.

members.name: verticalOffset
members.description:
A pixel value that will be added to the position calculated for the
given `verticalAlign`, in the direction of alignment. You can think
of it as increasing or decreasing the distance to the side of the
screen given by `verticalAlign`.

If `verticalAlign` is "top" or "middle", this offset will increase or
decrease the distance to the top side of the screen: a negative offset
will move the dropdown upwards; a positive one, downwards.

Conversely if `verticalAlign` is "bottom", this offset will increase
or decrease the distance to the bottom side of the screen: a negative
offset will move the dropdown downwards; a positive one, upwards.

A pixel value that will be added to the position calculated for the
given `horizontalAlign`, in the direction of alignment. You can think
of it as increasing or decreasing the distance to the side of the
screen given by `horizontalAlign`.

If `horizontalAlign` is "left" or "center", this offset will increase or
decrease the distance to the left side of the screen: a negative offset
will move the dropdown to the left; a positive one, to the right.

Conversely if `horizontalAlign` is "right", this offset will increase
or decrease the distance to the right side of the screen: a negative
offset will move the dropdown to the right; a positive one, to the left.

attributes.name: verticalOffset
attributes.description:
A pixel value that will be added to the position calculated for the
given `verticalAlign`, in the direction of alignment. You can think
of it as increasing or decreasing the distance to the side of the
screen given by `verticalAlign`.

If `verticalAlign` is "top" or "middle", this offset will increase or
decrease the distance to the top side of the screen: a negative offset
will move the dropdown upwards; a positive one, downwards.

Conversely if `verticalAlign` is "bottom", this offset will increase
or decrease the distance to the bottom side of the screen: a negative
offset will move the dropdown downwards; a positive one, upwards.

declarations.description:
An element to display formatted date and time.

The `date` property accepts Date object, Number as a timestamp or string
that will be parsed to the Date object.

This element uses the `Intl` interface which is available in IE 11+ browsers.

To format the date use [Intl.DateTimeFormat]
(https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/DateTimeFormat)
interface options.

The default value for each date-time component property is undefined,
but if all component properties are undefined, then year, month, and day
are assumed to be "numeric" (per spec).

### Example

```html
<date-time date="2010-12-10T11:50:45Z" year="numeric" month="narrow" day="numeric"></date-time>
```

The element provides accessibility by using the `time` element and setting
the `datetime` attribute on it.
declarations.name: DateTimeElement

members.name: locales
members.description:
A string with a BCP 47 language tag, or an array of such strings.
For the general form and interpretation of the locales argument,
see the Intl page.
The following Unicode extension keys are allowed:
- nu - Numbering system. Possible values include: "arab", "arabext",
"bali", "beng", "deva", "fullwide", "gujr", "guru", "hanidec", "khmr",
"knda", "laoo", "latn", "limb", "mlym", "mong", "mymr", "orya",
"tamldec", "telu", "thai", "tibt".
- ca - Calendar. Possible values include: "buddhist", "chinese",
"coptic", "ethioaa", "ethiopic", "gregory", "hebrew", "indian",
"islamic", "islamicc", "iso8601", "japanese", "persian", "roc".

declarations.description:
A web component written in plain JavaScript to render a 5 star rating.

By default it is an interactive element where the user can change the selection.
Add `readOnly` attribute/JS property to disable this behavior.

## Example

```html
<star-rating value="3"></star-rating>
```
### Styling

`<exchange-search-list-item>` provides the following custom properties and mixins for styling:

Custom property | Description | Default
----------------|-------------|----------
`--star-rating-width` | Icon width | `24px`
`--star-rating-height` | Icon width | `24px`
`--star-rating-unselected-color` | Icon color when not selected | `#eeeeee`
`--star-rating-selected-color` | Icon color when selected | `#fdd835`
`--star-rating-active-color` | Icon color when active (focus, hover) | `#e0be25`
declarations.name: StarRatingElement

members.name: notifyResize
members.description:
Can be called to manually notify a resizable and its descendant
resizables of a resize change.

members.name: assignParentResizable
members.description:
Used to assign the closest resizable ancestor to this resizable
if the ancestor detects a request for notifications.

members.name: stopResizeNotificationsFor
members.description:
Used to remove a resizable descendant from the list of descendants
that should be notified of a resize change.

members.name: resizerShouldNotify

parameters.name: element
parameters.description: A candidate descendant element that implements `ResizableElements`.

members.description:
This method can be overridden to filter nested elements that should or
should not be notified by the current element. Return true if an element
should be notified, or false if it should not be notified.

members.name: _subscribeIronResize

parameters.name: target
parameters.description: Element to listen to for `resize` events.

members.description:
Subscribe this element to listen to `resize` events on the given target.

Preferred over target.listen because the property "renamer" does not
understand to rename when the target is not specifically "this"

members.name: _unsubscribeIronResize

parameters.name: target
parameters.description: Element to listen to for `resize` events.

members.description:
Unsubscribe this element from listening to to `resize` events on the
given target.

Preferred over target.unlisten because the property "renamer" does not
understand to rename when the target is not specifically "this"

members.name: anypoint
members.description: Enables Anypoint theme.

members.name: outlined
members.description: Enables Material's outlined theme.

members.name: anypointChanged
members.description: To be used by child classes when the `anypoint` property change.

members.name: outlinedChanged
members.description: To be used by child classes when the `outlined` property change.

attributes.name: attrForItemTitle
attributes.description:
The attribute to use on menu items to look up the item title. Typing the
first letter of an item when the menu is open focuses that item. If
unset, `textContent` will be used.

attributes.name: useAriaSelected
attributes.description:
When set it adds `aria-selected` attribute to currently selected item.

The `aria-selected` attribute is invalid with default role of this
element ("menu"). If you manually change the role to some other that
accepts `aria-selected` attribute on children then set this property.

attributes.name: highlightAriaSelected
attributes.description:
When set the effect of calling `highlightNext()` or `highlightPrevious()`
will be setting `aria-selected` attribute. For proper accessibility use
with the combination with `useAriaSelected` attribute.

attributes.name: disabled
attributes.description: Whether or not this menu is disabled.

attributes.name: multi
attributes.description: If true, multiple selections are allowed.

attributes.name: selectedValues
attributes.description:
Gets or sets the selected elements. This is used instead of `selected`
when `multi` is true.

attributes.name: selectable
attributes.description:
This is a CSS selector string.  If this is set, only items that match the
CSS selector are selectable.

attributes.name: selectedClass
attributes.description: The class to set on elements when selected.

attributes.name: selectedAttribute
attributes.description: The attribute to set on elements when selected.

attributes.name: attrForSelected
attributes.description:
If you want to use an attribute value or property of an element for
`selected` instead of the index, set this to the name of the attribute
or property. Hyphenated values are converted to camel case when used to
look up the property of a selectable element. Camel cased values are
*not* converted to hyphenated values for attribute lookup. It's
recommended that you provide the hyphenated form of the name so that
selection works in both cases. (Use `attr-or-property-name` instead of
`attrOrPropertyName`.)

attributes.name: selected
attributes.description: The selected element. The default is to use the index of the item.

attributes.name: activateEvent
attributes.description:
The event that fires from items when they are selected. Selectable
will listen for this event from items and update the selection state.
Set to empty string to listen to no events.

attributes.name: fallbackSelection
attributes.description: Default fallback if the selection based on selected with `attrForSelected` is not found.

attributes.name: anypoint
attributes.description: Enables Anypoint theme.

attributes.name: outlined
attributes.description: Enables Material's outlined theme.

members.name: _onEscKey

members.name: _resetTabindices
members.description:
Resets all tabindex attributes to the appropriate value based on the
current selection state. The appropriate value is `0` (focusable) for
the default selected item, and `-1` (not keyboard focusable) for all
other items. Also sets the correct initial values for aria-selected
attribute, true for default selected item and false for others.

members.name: select

parameters.name: value
parameters.description: the value to select.

members.description:
Selects the given value. If the `multi` property is true, then the selected
state of the `value` will be toggled; otherwise the `value` will be
selected.

members.name: focusPrevious
members.description:
Focuses the previous item (relative to the currently focused item) in the
menu, disabled items will be skipped.
Loop until length + 1 to handle case of single item in menu.

members.name: focusNext
members.description:
Focuses the next item (relative to the currently focused item) in the
menu, disabled items will be skipped.

members.name: highlightNext
members.description:
Highlights, by setting the `highlight` css class, the next available element.
If there's no highlighted item but there is a selection (focused item)
then a next item after the selection is selected.

members.name: highlightPrevious
members.description:
Highlights, by setting the `highlight` css class, the previous available element.
If there's no highlighted item but there is a selection (focused item)
then a previous item before the selection is selected.

members.description:

all items correctly reflect selection state.

attributes.name: attrForItemTitle
attributes.description:
The attribute to use on menu items to look up the item title. Typing the
first letter of an item when the menu is open focuses that item. If
unset, `textContent` will be used.

attributes.name: useAriaSelected
attributes.description:
When set it adds `aria-selected` attribute to currently selected item.

The `aria-selected` attribute is invalid with default role of this
element ("menu"). If you manually change the role to some other that
accepts `aria-selected` attribute on children then set this property.

attributes.name: highlightAriaSelected
attributes.description:
When set the effect of calling `highlightNext()` or `highlightPrevious()`
will be setting `aria-selected` attribute. For proper accessibility use
with the combination with `useAriaSelected` attribute.

attributes.name: disabled
attributes.description: Whether or not this menu is disabled.

attributes.name: multi
attributes.description: If true, multiple selections are allowed.

attributes.name: selectedValues
attributes.description:
Gets or sets the selected elements. This is used instead of `selected`
when `multi` is true.

attributes.name: selectable
attributes.description:
This is a CSS selector string.  If this is set, only items that match the
CSS selector are selectable.

attributes.name: selectedClass
attributes.description: The class to set on elements when selected.

attributes.name: selectedAttribute
attributes.description: The attribute to set on elements when selected.

attributes.name: attrForSelected
attributes.description:
If you want to use an attribute value or property of an element for
`selected` instead of the index, set this to the name of the attribute
or property. Hyphenated values are converted to camel case when used to
look up the property of a selectable element. Camel cased values are
*not* converted to hyphenated values for attribute lookup. It's
recommended that you provide the hyphenated form of the name so that
selection works in both cases. (Use `attr-or-property-name` instead of
`attrOrPropertyName`.)

attributes.name: selected
attributes.description: The selected element. The default is to use the index of the item.

attributes.name: activateEvent
attributes.description:
The event that fires from items when they are selected. Selectable
will listen for this event from items and update the selection state.
Set to empty string to listen to no events.

attributes.name: fallbackSelection
attributes.description: Default fallback if the selection based on selected with `attrForSelected` is not found.

attributes.name: anypoint
attributes.description: Enables Anypoint theme.

attributes.name: outlined
attributes.description: Enables Material's outlined theme.

members.name: fitInto
members.description: The element to fit `this` into.

members.name: sizingTarget
members.description:
The element that will receive a `max-height`/`width`. By default it is
the same as `this`, but it can be set to a child element. This is useful,
for example, for implementing a scrolling region inside the element.

members.name: noOverlap
members.description:
Will position the element around the positionTarget without overlapping
it.

members.name: positionTarget
members.description:
The element that should be used to position the element. If not set, it
will default to the parent node.

members.name: horizontalAlign
members.description:
The orientation against which to align the element horizontally
relative to the `positionTarget`. Possible values are "left", "right",
"center", "auto".

members.name: verticalAlign
members.description:
The orientation against which to align the element vertically
relative to the `positionTarget`. Possible values are "top", "bottom",
"middle", "auto".

members.name: dynamicAlign
members.description:
If true, it will use `horizontalAlign` and `verticalAlign` values as
preferred alignment and if there's not enough space, it will pick the
values which minimize the cropping.

members.name: horizontalOffset
members.description:
A pixel value that will be added to the position calculated for the
given `horizontalAlign`, in the direction of alignment. You can think
of it as increasing or decreasing the distance to the side of the
screen given by `horizontalAlign`.

If `horizontalAlign` is "left" or "center", this offset will increase or
decrease the distance to the left side of the screen: a negative offset
will move the dropdown to the left; a positive one, to the right.

Conversely if `horizontalAlign` is "right", this offset will increase
or decrease the distance to the right side of the screen: a negative
offset will move the dropdown to the right; a positive one, to the left.

members.name: verticalOffset
members.description:
A pixel value that will be added to the position calculated for the
given `verticalAlign`, in the direction of alignment. You can think
of it as increasing or decreasing the distance to the side of the
screen given by `verticalAlign`.

If `verticalAlign` is "top" or "middle", this offset will increase or
decrease the distance to the top side of the screen: a negative offset
will move the dropdown upwards; a positive one, downwards.

Conversely if `verticalAlign` is "bottom", this offset will increase
or decrease the distance to the bottom side of the screen: a negative
offset will move the dropdown downwards; a positive one, upwards.

members.name: autoFitOnAttach
members.description: Set to true to auto-fit on attach.

members.name: fitPositionTarget
members.description: When set it fits the positioning target width.

members.name: _defaultPositionTarget
members.description:
The element that should be used to position the element,
if no position target is configured.

members.name: _localeHorizontalAlign
members.description: The horizontal align value, accounting for the RTL/LTR text direction.

members.name: __shouldPosition
members.description: True if the element should be positioned instead of centered.

members.name: fit
members.description: Positions and fits the element into the `fitInto` element.

members.name: _discoverInfo
members.description: Memoize information needed to position and size the target element.

members.name: resetFit
members.description:
Resets the target element's position and size constraints, and clear
the memoized data.

members.name: refit
members.description:
Equivalent to calling `resetFit()` and `fit()`. Useful to call this after
the element or the `fitInto` element has been resized, or if any of the
positioning properties (e.g. `horizontalAlign, verticalAlign`) is updated.
It preserves the scroll position of the sizingTarget.

members.name: position
members.description: Positions the element according to `horizontalAlign, verticalAlign`.

members.name: constrain
members.description:
Constrains the size of the element to `fitInto` by setting `max-height`
and/or `max-width`.

members.name: center
members.description:
Centers horizontally and vertically if not already positioned. This also
sets `position:fixed`.

resizables of a resize change.

members.name: assignParentResizable
members.description:
Used to assign the closest resizable ancestor to this resizable
if the ancestor detects a request for notifications.

members.name: stopResizeNotificationsFor
members.description:
Used to remove a resizable descendant from the list of descendants
that should be notified of a resize change.

members.name: noAutoFocus
members.description:
Set to true to disable auto-focusing the overlay or child nodes with
the `autofocus` attribute` when the overlay is opened.

members.name: noCancelOnEscKey
members.description: Set to true to disable canceling the overlay with the ESC key.

members.name: noCancelOnOutsideClick
members.description: Set to true to disable canceling the overlay by clicking outside it.

members.name: closingReason
members.description:
Contains the reason(s) this overlay was last closed (see `closed`). `OverlayElement` provides the `canceled`
reason; implementers of the behavior can provide other reasons in
addition to `canceled`.

members.name: restoreFocusOnClose
members.description: Set to true to enable restoring of focus when overlay is closed.

members.name: allowClickThrough
members.description:
Set to true to allow clicks to go through overlays.
When the user clicks outside this overlay, the click may
close the overlay below.

members.name: alwaysOnTop
members.description: Set to true to keep overlay always on top.

members.name: _manager
members.description: Shortcut to access to the overlay manager.

members.name: _focusedChild
members.description: The node being focused.

members.name: opened
members.description: True if the overlay is currently displayed.

members.name: canceled
members.description: True if the overlay was canceled when it was last closed.

members.name: _canceled
members.description: True if the overlay was canceled when it was last closed.

members.name: withBackdrop
members.description:
Set to true to display a backdrop behind the overlay. It traps the focus
within the light DOM of the overlay.

members.name: scrollAction
members.description:
Determines which action to perform when scroll outside an opened overlay
happens. Possible values: lock - blocks scrolling from happening, refit -
computes the new position on the overlay cancel - causes the overlay to
close

members.name: backdropElement
members.description: The backdrop element.

members.name: _focusNode
members.description: Returns the node to give focus to.

members.name: _focusableNodes
members.description:
Array of nodes that can receive focus (overlay included), ordered by
`tabindex`. This is used to retrieve which is the first and last focusable
nodes in order to wrap the focus for overlays `with-backdrop`.

If you know what is your content (specifically the first and last focusable
children), you can override this method to return only `[firstFocusable,
lastFocusable];`

attributes.name: sizingTarget
attributes.description:
The element that will receive a `max-height`/`width`. By default it is
the same as `this`, but it can be set to a child element. This is useful,
for example, for implementing a scrolling region inside the element.

attributes.name: noOverlap
attributes.description:
Will position the element around the positionTarget without overlapping
it.

attributes.name: positionTarget
attributes.description:
The element that should be used to position the element. If not set, it
will default to the parent node.

attributes.name: horizontalAlign
attributes.description:
The orientation against which to align the element horizontally
relative to the `positionTarget`. Possible values are "left", "right",
"center", "auto".

attributes.name: verticalAlign
attributes.description:
The orientation against which to align the element vertically
relative to the `positionTarget`. Possible values are "top", "bottom",
"middle", "auto".

attributes.name: dynamicAlign
attributes.description:
If true, it will use `horizontalAlign` and `verticalAlign` values as
preferred alignment and if there's not enough space, it will pick the
values which minimize the cropping.

attributes.name: horizontalOffset
attributes.description:
A pixel value that will be added to the position calculated for the
given `horizontalAlign`, in the direction of alignment. You can think
of it as increasing or decreasing the distance to the side of the
screen given by `horizontalAlign`.

If `horizontalAlign` is "left" or "center", this offset will increase or
decrease the distance to the left side of the screen: a negative offset
will move the dropdown to the left; a positive one, to the right.

Conversely if `horizontalAlign` is "right", this offset will increase
or decrease the distance to the right side of the screen: a negative
offset will move the dropdown to the right; a positive one, to the left.

attributes.name: verticalOffset
attributes.description:
A pixel value that will be added to the position calculated for the
given `verticalAlign`, in the direction of alignment. You can think
of it as increasing or decreasing the distance to the side of the
screen given by `verticalAlign`.

If `verticalAlign` is "top" or "middle", this offset will increase or
decrease the distance to the top side of the screen: a negative offset
will move the dropdown upwards; a positive one, downwards.

Conversely if `verticalAlign` is "bottom", this offset will increase
or decrease the distance to the bottom side of the screen: a negative
offset will move the dropdown downwards; a positive one, upwards.

members.description:
Array of nodes that can receive focus (overlay included), ordered by
`tabindex`. This is used to retrieve which is the first and last focusable
nodes in order to wrap the focus for overlays `with-backdrop`.

If you know what is your content (specifically the first and last focusable
children), you can override this method to return only `[firstFocusable,
lastFocusable];`

members.name: refit
members.description:
Equivalent to calling `resetFit()` and `fit()`. Useful to call this after
the element or the `fitInto` element has been resized, or if any of the
positioning properties (e.g. `horizontalAlign, verticalAlign`) is updated.
It preserves the scroll position of the sizingTarget.

members.name: scrollTarget

Specifies the element that will handle the scroll event on the behalf of the current element. This is typically a reference to an element, but there are a few more possibilities: ### Elements id ```html
``` In this case, the `scrollTarget` will point to the outer div element. ### Document scrolling For document scrolling, you can use the reserved word `document`: ```html ``` ### Elements reference ```js appHeader.scrollTarget = document.querySelector('#scrollable-element'); ```

members.name: elevation
members.description:
The z-depth of this element, from 0-5. Setting to 0 will remove the
shadow, and each increasing number greater than 0 will be "deeper"
than the last.
This is for MD implementation.

members.name: noink
members.description: When set ripple effect is not rendered.

members.name: flat
members.description: When set it won't elevate the element, even when high emphasis.

members.name: emphasis
members.description:
Button emphasis in the UI.

Possible values:
- `low` - Text buttons are typically used for less important actions.
- `medium` - Outlined buttons are used for more emphasis than text buttons due to the stroke.
- `high` - Contained buttons have more emphasis, as they use use a color fill and shadow.

Default is "low".

members.name: _calculateElevation
members.description:
Computes current elevation for the material design.
The `emphasis` property is set when the updates are committed.

members.name: _transitionEndHandler
members.description:

declarations.description:
`anypoint-radio-button`

Anypoint styled radio button.

## Usage

Install element:

```
npm i --save @anypoint-components/anypoint-radio-button
```

Import into your app:

```html
<script type="module" src="node_modules/@anypoint-components/anypoint-radio-button.js"></script>
```

Or into another component

```javascript
import '@anypoint-components/anypoint-radio-button.js';
```

Use it:

```html
<paper-radio-group selectable="anypoint-radio-button">
 <anypoint-radio-button name="a">Apple</anypoint-radio-button>
 <anypoint-radio-button name="b">Banana</anypoint-radio-button>
 <anypoint-radio-button name="c">Orange</anypoint-radio-button>
</paper-radio-group>
```

declarations.description:
A web component that groups custom radio buttons and handles selection inside
the group.

Requirements for children:
- must have role="radio" attribute
- must have name attribute
- radio state change must be notified via `change` event.

Radio buttons with the same name inside their group will have single selection.
This means when selecting a radio button any other currently selected button
will be deselected.

Also. when initializing the component, only last selected component keeps the
selection.
When new checked radio button is inserted into the group the selection is passed to the newly
arriving element.

This behavior is consistent with native DOM API.

The group element exposes `selected` property that holds a reference to
currently selected radio button.

Example

```
<anypoint-radio-group>
 <anypoint-radio-button name="option"></anypoint-radio-button>
 <other-control role="button" name="option" checked></other-control>
</anypoint-radio-group>
```

members.name: _resetTabindices
members.description:
Resets all tabindex attributes to the appropriate value based on the
current selection state. The appropriate value is `0` (focusable) for
the default selected item, and `-1` (not keyboard focusable) for all
other items. Also sets the correct initial values for aria-selected
attribute, true for default selected item and false for others.

parameters.name: value
parameters.description: the value to select.

members.description:
Selects the given value. If the `multi` property is true, then the selected
state of the `value` will be toggled; otherwise the `value` will be
selected.

members.name: focusPrevious
members.description:
Focuses the previous item (relative to the currently focused item) in the
menu, disabled items will be skipped.
Loop until length + 1 to handle case of single item in menu.

members.name: focusNext
members.description:
Focuses the next item (relative to the currently focused item) in the
menu, disabled items will be skipped.

members.name: highlightNext
members.description:
Highlights, by setting the `highlight` css class, the next available element.
If there's no highlighted item but there is a selection (focused item)
then a next item after the selection is selected.

members.name: highlightPrevious
members.description:
Highlights, by setting the `highlight` css class, the previous available element.
If there's no highlighted item but there is a selection (focused item)
then a previous item before the selection is selected.

members.name: selectedAttribute

members.name: attrForSelected
members.description:
If you want to use an attribute value or property of an element for
`selected` instead of the index, set this to the name of the attribute
or property. Hyphenated values are converted to camel case when used to
look up the property of a selectable element. Camel cased values are
*not* converted to hyphenated values for attribute lookup. It's
recommended that you provide the hyphenated form of the name so that
selection works in both cases. (Use `attr-or-property-name` instead of
`attrOrPropertyName`.)

members.description:
Binds this to the `<input>`'s `autocapitalize` property.

Possible values are:

- `off` or `none`: No autocapitalization is applied (all letters default to lowercase)
- `on` or `sentences`: The first letter of each sentence defaults to a capital letter;
 all other letters default to lowercase
- `words`: The first letter of each word defaults to a capital letter; all other letters default to lowercase
- `characters`: All letters should default to uppercase

members.name: fitInto
members.description: The element to fit `this` into.

members.name: sizingTarget
members.description:
The element that will receive a `max-height`/`width`. By default it is
the same as `this`, but it can be set to a child element. This is useful,
for example, for implementing a scrolling region inside the element.

members.name: noOverlap
members.description:
Will position the element around the positionTarget without overlapping
it.

members.name: positionTarget
members.description:
The element that should be used to position the element. If not set, it
will default to the parent node.

members.name: horizontalAlign
members.description:
The orientation against which to align the element horizontally
relative to the `positionTarget`. Possible values are "left", "right",
"center", "auto".

members.name: verticalAlign
members.description:
The orientation against which to align the element vertically
relative to the `positionTarget`. Possible values are "top", "bottom",
"middle", "auto".

members.name: dynamicAlign
members.description:
If true, it will use `horizontalAlign` and `verticalAlign` values as
preferred alignment and if there's not enough space, it will pick the
values which minimize the cropping.

members.name: horizontalOffset
members.description:
A pixel value that will be added to the position calculated for the
given `horizontalAlign`, in the direction of alignment. You can think
of it as increasing or decreasing the distance to the side of the
screen given by `horizontalAlign`.

If `horizontalAlign` is "left" or "center", this offset will increase or
decrease the distance to the left side of the screen: a negative offset
will move the dropdown to the left; a positive one, to the right.

Conversely if `horizontalAlign` is "right", this offset will increase
or decrease the distance to the right side of the screen: a negative
offset will move the dropdown to the right; a positive one, to the left.

members.name: verticalOffset
members.description:
A pixel value that will be added to the position calculated for the
given `verticalAlign`, in the direction of alignment. You can think
of it as increasing or decreasing the distance to the side of the
screen given by `verticalAlign`.

If `verticalAlign` is "top" or "middle", this offset will increase or
decrease the distance to the top side of the screen: a negative offset
will move the dropdown upwards; a positive one, downwards.

Conversely if `verticalAlign` is "bottom", this offset will increase
or decrease the distance to the bottom side of the screen: a negative
offset will move the dropdown downwards; a positive one, upwards.

members.name: autoFitOnAttach
members.description: Set to true to auto-fit on attach.

members.name: fitPositionTarget
members.description: When set it fits the positioning target width.

members.name: _defaultPositionTarget
members.description:
The element that should be used to position the element,
if no position target is configured.

members.name: _localeHorizontalAlign
members.description: The horizontal align value, accounting for the RTL/LTR text direction.

members.name: __shouldPosition
members.description: True if the element should be positioned instead of centered.

members.name: fit
members.description: Positions and fits the element into the `fitInto` element.

members.name: _discoverInfo
members.description: Memoize information needed to position and size the target element.

members.name: resetFit
members.description:
Resets the target element's position and size constraints, and clear
the memoized data.

members.name: refit
members.description:
Equivalent to calling `resetFit()` and `fit()`. Useful to call this after
the element or the `fitInto` element has been resized, or if any of the
positioning properties (e.g. `horizontalAlign, verticalAlign`) is updated.
It preserves the scroll position of the sizingTarget.

members.name: position
members.description: Positions the element according to `horizontalAlign, verticalAlign`.

members.name: constrain
members.description:
Constrains the size of the element to `fitInto` by setting `max-height`
and/or `max-width`.

members.name: center
members.description:
Centers horizontally and vertically if not already positioned. This also
sets `position:fixed`.

members.name: notifyResize
members.description:
Can be called to manually notify a resizable and its descendant
resizables of a resize change.

members.name: assignParentResizable
members.description:
Used to assign the closest resizable ancestor to this resizable
if the ancestor detects a request for notifications.

members.name: stopResizeNotificationsFor
members.description:
Used to remove a resizable descendant from the list of descendants
that should be notified of a resize change.

members.name: resizerShouldNotify

parameters.name: element

members.description:

should not be notified by the current element. Return true if an element
should be notified, or false if it should not be notified.

understand to rename when the target is not specifically "this"

attributes.name: noAutoFocus
attributes.description:
Set to true to disable auto-focusing the overlay or child nodes with
the `autofocus` attribute` when the overlay is opened.

attributes.name: noCancelOnEscKey
attributes.description: Set to true to disable canceling the overlay with the ESC key.

attributes.name: noCancelOnOutsideClick
attributes.description: Set to true to disable canceling the overlay by clicking outside it.

attributes.name: closingReason
attributes.description:
Contains the reason(s) this overlay was last closed (see `closed`). `OverlayElement` provides the `canceled`
reason; implementers of the behavior can provide other reasons in
addition to `canceled`.

attributes.name: restoreFocusOnClose
attributes.description: Set to true to enable restoring of focus when overlay is closed.

attributes.name: allowClickThrough
attributes.description:
Set to true to allow clicks to go through overlays.
When the user clicks outside this overlay, the click may
close the overlay below.

attributes.name: alwaysOnTop
attributes.description: Set to true to keep overlay always on top.

attributes.name: opened
attributes.description: True if the overlay is currently displayed.

attributes.name: withBackdrop
attributes.description:
Set to true to display a backdrop behind the overlay. It traps the focus
within the light DOM of the overlay.

attributes.name: scrollAction
attributes.description:
Determines which action to perform when scroll outside an opened overlay
happens. Possible values: lock - blocks scrolling from happening, refit -
computes the new position on the overlay cancel - causes the overlay to
close

attributes.name: fitInto
attributes.description: The element to fit `this` into.

attributes.name: sizingTarget
attributes.description:
The element that will receive a `max-height`/`width`. By default it is
the same as `this`, but it can be set to a child element. This is useful,
for example, for implementing a scrolling region inside the element.

attributes.name: noOverlap
attributes.description:
Will position the element around the positionTarget without overlapping
it.

attributes.name: positionTarget
attributes.description:
The element that should be used to position the element. If not set, it
will default to the parent node.

attributes.name: horizontalAlign
attributes.description:
The orientation against which to align the element horizontally
relative to the `positionTarget`. Possible values are "left", "right",
"center", "auto".

attributes.name: verticalAlign
attributes.description:
The orientation against which to align the element vertically
relative to the `positionTarget`. Possible values are "top", "bottom",
"middle", "auto".

attributes.name: dynamicAlign
attributes.description:
If true, it will use `horizontalAlign` and `verticalAlign` values as
preferred alignment and if there's not enough space, it will pick the
values which minimize the cropping.

attributes.name: horizontalOffset
attributes.description:
A pixel value that will be added to the position calculated for the
given `horizontalAlign`, in the direction of alignment. You can think
of it as increasing or decreasing the distance to the side of the
screen given by `horizontalAlign`.

If `horizontalAlign` is "left" or "center", this offset will increase or
decrease the distance to the left side of the screen: a negative offset
will move the dropdown to the left; a positive one, to the right.

Conversely if `horizontalAlign` is "right", this offset will increase
or decrease the distance to the right side of the screen: a negative
offset will move the dropdown to the right; a positive one, to the left.

attributes.name: verticalOffset
attributes.description:
A pixel value that will be added to the position calculated for the
given `verticalAlign`, in the direction of alignment. You can think
of it as increasing or decreasing the distance to the side of the
screen given by `verticalAlign`.

If `verticalAlign` is "top" or "middle", this offset will increase or
decrease the distance to the top side of the screen: a negative offset
will move the dropdown upwards; a positive one, downwards.

Conversely if `verticalAlign` is "bottom", this offset will increase
or decrease the distance to the bottom side of the screen: a negative
offset will move the dropdown downwards; a positive one, upwards.

attributes.name: autoFitOnAttach
attributes.description: Set to true to auto-fit on attach.

attributes.name: fitPositionTarget
attributes.description: When set it fits the positioning target width.

declarations.description:
An element that coordinates the flow of resize events between "resizers" (elements that
control the size or hidden state of their children) and "resizables" (elements
that need to be notified when they are resized or un-hidden by their parents
in order to take action on their new measurements).
declarations.name: ResizableElement

members.name: notifyResize
members.description:
Can be called to manually notify a resizable and its descendant
resizables of a resize change.

members.name: assignParentResizable
members.description:
Used to assign the closest resizable ancestor to this resizable
if the ancestor detects a request for notifications.

members.name: stopResizeNotificationsFor
members.description:
Used to remove a resizable descendant from the list of descendants
that should be notified of a resize change.

members.name: resizerShouldNotify

parameters.name: element
parameters.description: A candidate descendant element that implements `ResizableElements`.

members.description:

should not be notified by the current element. Return true if an element
should be notified, or false if it should not be notified.

element ("menu"). If you manually change the role to some other that
accepts `aria-selected` attribute on children then set this property.

will be setting `aria-selected` attribute. For proper accessibility use
with the combination with `useAriaSelected` attribute.

members.name: _resetTabindices
members.description:
Resets all tabindex attributes to the appropriate value based on the
current selection state. The appropriate value is `0` (focusable) for
the default selected item, and `-1` (not keyboard focusable) for all
other items. Also sets the correct initial values for aria-selected
attribute, true for default selected item and false for others.

members.description:
Selects the given value. If the `multi` property is true, then the selected
state of the `value` will be toggled; otherwise the `value` will be
selected.

members.name: focusPrevious
members.description:
Focuses the previous item (relative to the currently focused item) in the
menu, disabled items will be skipped.
Loop until length + 1 to handle case of single item in menu.

members.name: focusNext
members.description:
Focuses the next item (relative to the currently focused item) in the
menu, disabled items will be skipped.

members.name: highlightNext
members.description:
Highlights, by setting the `highlight` css class, the next available element.
If there's no highlighted item but there is a selection (focused item)
then a next item after the selection is selected.

members.name: highlightPrevious
members.description:
Highlights, by setting the `highlight` css class, the previous available element.
If there's no highlighted item but there is a selection (focused item)
then a previous item before the selection is selected.

members.description:

`selected` instead of the index, set this to the name of the attribute
or property. Hyphenated values are converted to camel case when used to
look up the property of a selectable element. Camel cased values are
*not* converted to hyphenated values for attribute lookup. It's

selection works in both cases. (Use `attr-or-property-name` instead of
`attrOrPropertyName`.)

attributes.name: attrForItemTitle
attributes.description:
The attribute to use on menu items to look up the item title. Typing the
first letter of an item when the menu is open focuses that item. If
unset, `textContent` will be used.

attributes.name: useAriaSelected
attributes.description:
When set it adds `aria-selected` attribute to currently selected item.

The `aria-selected` attribute is invalid with default role of this
element ("menu"). If you manually change the role to some other that
accepts `aria-selected` attribute on children then set this property.

attributes.name: highlightAriaSelected
attributes.description:
When set the effect of calling `highlightNext()` or `highlightPrevious()`
will be setting `aria-selected` attribute. For proper accessibility use
with the combination with `useAriaSelected` attribute.

attributes.name: disabled
attributes.description: Whether or not this menu is disabled.

attributes.name: multi
attributes.description: If true, multiple selections are allowed.

attributes.name: selectedValues
attributes.description:
Gets or sets the selected elements. This is used instead of `selected`
when `multi` is true.

attributes.name: selectable
attributes.description:
This is a CSS selector string.  If this is set, only items that match the
CSS selector are selectable.

attributes.name: selectedClass
attributes.description: The class to set on elements when selected.

attributes.name: selectedAttribute
attributes.description: The attribute to set on elements when selected.

attributes.name: attrForSelected
attributes.description:
If you want to use an attribute value or property of an element for
`selected` instead of the index, set this to the name of the attribute
or property. Hyphenated values are converted to camel case when used to
look up the property of a selectable element. Camel cased values are
*not* converted to hyphenated values for attribute lookup. It's
recommended that you provide the hyphenated form of the name so that
selection works in both cases. (Use `attr-or-property-name` instead of
`attrOrPropertyName`.)

attributes.name: selected
attributes.description: The selected element. The default is to use the index of the item.

attributes.name: activateEvent
attributes.description:
The event that fires from items when they are selected. Selectable
will listen for this event from items and update the selection state.
Set to empty string to listen to no events.

attributes.name: fallbackSelection
attributes.description: Default fallback if the selection based on selected with `attrForSelected` is not found.

attributes.description: Enables Anypoint theme.

attributes.description: Enables Material's outlined theme.
